Targeted Pharmacotherapy in Progressive Familial Intrahepatic Cholestasis Type 2: Evidence for Improvement of Cholestasis With 4-Phenylbutyrate impaired biliary BA secretion leads Emmanuel Gonzales,1,2 Brigitte Grosse,2 Brice Schuller,2 Anne Davit-Spraul,3 Filomena Conti,4 Catherine Guettier,5 Doris Cassio,2 and Emmanuel Jacquemin1,2

Progressive familial intrahepatic cholestasis type 2 (PFIC2) is a result of mutations in ABCB11 encoding bile salt export pump (BSEP), the canalicular bile salt export pump of hepatocyte. In some PFIC2 patients with missense mutations, BSEP is not detected at the canaliculus owing to mistrafﬁcking of BSEP mutants. In vitro, chaperone drugs, such as 4- phenylbutyrate (4-PB), have been shown to partially correct mistrafﬁcking. Four PFIC2 patients harboring at least one missense mutation (p.G982R, p.R1128C, and p.T1210P) were treated orally with 4-PB and followed prospectively. Patient mutations were reproduced in a Bsep/green ﬂuorescent protein plasmid. Cellular localization of the resulting Bsep mutants was studied in a hepatocellular line (Can 10), and effects of treatment with 4-PB and/or ursodeoxycholic acid (UDCA) were assessed. In Can 10 cells, Bsep mutants were detected in the endoplasmic reticulum instead of at the canalicular membrane. Treatment with 4-PB and UDCA partially corrected Bsep mutant targeting. With 4-PB, we observed, in all patients, a decrease of pruritus and serum bile acid concentration (BAC) as well as an improvement of serum liver tests. Pathological liver injuries improved, and BSEP, which was not detected at the canalicular membrane before treatment, appeared at the canalicular mem- brane. Bile analyses showed an increase in BAC with 4-PB. Patient conditions remained sta- ble with a median follow-up of 40 months (range, 3-53), and treatment tolerance was good. Conclusion: 4-PB therapy may be efﬁcient in selected patients with PFIC2 owing to ABCB11 missense mutations affecting BSEP canalicular targeting. Bile secretion improvement may be a result of the ability of 4-PB to retarget mutated BSEP. (HEPATOLOGY 2015;62:558-566) See Editorial on Page 349

cytes, ongoing hepatocellular damage, and increased risk of hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC). Clinical signs of cholestasis usually appear in the ﬁrst months of life with jaundice and pruritus. Patients develop ﬁbrosis and end-stage liver disease before adulthood. Medical therapy with ursodeoxycholic acid (UDCA), rifampi- cin, and surgical therapy, such as biliary diversion, may provide some symptomatic relief. Nevertheless, in is the majority of cases, required because of unremitting pruritus, hepatic failure, or HCC.2 In the liver of most children with liver transplantation (LT) HEPATOLOGY, Vol. 62, No. 2, 2015 PFIC2, BSEP is not detected at the canaliculus of hepatocytes.1,2 Involved mutations include nonsense mutations leading to premature protein truncation and/or failure of protein production; nonetheless, mis- sense mutations are also common defects.1,2 In vitro studies performed in various cell lines show that some missense mutations affect protein processing and traf- ﬁcking, thereby causing retention in the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) and subsequent ER-associated degrada- tion.3-9 4-phenylbutyrate (4-PB), a clinically approved pharmacological chaperone,10 has been shown in vitro to retarget some mislocalized Bsep mutants at the plasma membrane,5,6 as well as other mutated apical transporters.11-14 In 2 patients with PFIC2, owing to homozygous missense mutations, preliminary studies (including one from our group) suggested that treat- ment with 4-PB could result in clinical and biological condition improvement by increasing BSEP mutant expression at the canalicular membrane, resulting in an increase of biliary BA secretion.15,16

Treatment with 4-PB was started in patients 1-4 at the ages of 10, 10, 17, and 22 years, respectively, after in vitro studies of the missense mutants identiﬁed in the patients. Before starting on 4- PB, written informed consent was obtained from each family, according to the guidelines of the local ethical committee. For patient 1, the short-term effects of 4-PB have been previously reported.15 Treatment With 4-PB. 4-PB therapy was started at a daily dose varying from approximately 150-250 mg per kilogram of body weight, divided into two oral doses of sodium phenylbutyrate (AMMONAPS; Swed- ish Orphan International AB, Stockholm, Sweden). For some patients, the dose was increased to a maximum of 500 mg/kg body weight per day or of 20 g per day, as recommended (Table 1).10 In all patients, UDCA and rifampicin were maintained without a change of dosage. Patients were followed prospectively.

Itching was quantiﬁed by the medical staff, the parents, and/or the patient himself using a visual analog scale (graduated from 0 to 10), during day- and nighttime. A score of 0 indicates no pruritus, whereas a score of 10 indicates unremitting pruritus with a severely impaired quality of life. Patient muta- tions p.A257V, p.G982R, p.R1128C, and p.T1210P were introduced in a pEGFP-N1 vector (Clontech Laboratories, Inc., Mountain View, CA) encoding a rat Bsep/green ﬂuorescent protein (GFP) fusion protein5 (a gift of J.L. Boyer, Yale University School of Medi- cine, New Haven, CT) using the QuickChange Light- ning Site-Directed Mutagenesis kit (Stratagene, Santa Clara, CA), according to the manufacturer’s instruc- tions. The sequences of the primers used for mutagen- esis are detailed in Supporting Table 1. Successful mutagenesis was veriﬁed by sequencing of the whole constructs. Rat Bsep plasmid was used because of the high degree of homology with human BSEP and the higher level of expression in cultured cells.3

Cell Culture, Transfection, and Treatments. Can 10, a rat hepatocellular polarized line, that expresses only a minimal level of Bsep was used.19 Cells were cultured as previously described.19 Can 10 cells, plated at 1.5 3 104/cm22 onto glass coverslips (18 mm diameter) in 12-well plates, were transiently transfected at day 3 of culture with Bsepwt, BsepA257V, BsepG982R, BsepR1128C, or BsepT1210P plasmid, using Fugene Xtrem HP (Roche Diagnostics, Meylan, France), according to the manufacturer’s instructions. Six hours after transfection, cells were either cultured during 24 hours at 27(cid:3)C or grown during 24 hours at 37(cid:3)C with or without 1 mM of 4-PB (diluted in phosphate- buffered saline; Biovision, Clinisciences, Montrouge, France), 50 mM of UDCA (diluted in dimethyl sulfox- ide [DMSO]), and 50 mM of UDCA plus 1 mM of 4-PB.

Hubbard [Baltimore, MD] and was used at 1:200); and rat anti-zonula occludens 1 (ZO-1; anti-ZO-1 Ab was a gift from B.R. Stevenson [Edmonton, Alberta, Canada] and was used undi- then incubated for 15 luted). Cells were rinsed, minutes appropriate Alexa- conjugated secondary Abs (1:500; Molecular Probes, Eugene, OR). The coverslips, mounted in mounting media (Sigma-Aldrich Chimie, Lyon, France), were examined with a Zeiss Axioskop epiﬂuorescence micro- scope (Carl Zeiss, Jena, Germany) equipped with a 403 oil-immersion objective. Images were collected with a CCD camera (ORCA; Hamamatsu Photonics K.K.,) and digitized with the HCI imaging software (Hamamatsu Photonics K.K., Hamamatsu City, Japan). Alternatively, cells were examined with a confo- cal microscope (Eclipse TE-2000-Nikon-C1; Nikon, Tokyo, Japan) equipped with a 603 objective and xy optical sections were taken in 0.3 lm steps. Images were processed using Photoshop 7 software (Adobe Systems Incorporated, San Jose, CA).

Quantiﬁcation of Cells Targeting Bsep to the Canalicular Pole. Cells expressing wild-type (WT) and mutated Bsep and forming bile canaliculi (BC) were examined by epiﬂuorescence microscopy. BC were identiﬁed by phase contrast and by immunolocal- ization of ZO-1 (a protein present at the tight junc- tions that seal the BC) or DPPIV (a protein localized at the canalicular membrane). The percentage of cells with Bsep-GFP enrichment at the canalicular pole was determined (40-100 cells coverslip, mean of two coverslips per culture, three to nine inde- pendent cultures). Statistical Analysis. Data are expressed as means 6 standard deviation. Statistical analyses were performed using the Student t test, with a P value <0.05 being con- sidered statistically signiﬁcant. 4-PB and UDCA Increase BsepG982R, BsepR1128C, and BsepT1210P Trafﬁcking to the Canalicular Membrane. Treatment with 4-PB, UDCA, as well as incubation at 27(cid:3)C, the latter being known to stabilize misfolded mutant proteins,4-6,8,20 partially corrected BsepG982R, BsepR1128C, and BsepT1210P targeting to the canalicular membrane. The combination of treatments with 4-PB and UDCA further increased canalicular tar- geting of BsepR1128C, BsepT1210P, and, to a lesser extent, of BsepG982R (Fig. 2A and Supporting Figs. 1–3). After treatments, confocal analyses showed a partial colocaliza- tion of these Bsep mutants with the canalicular protein, DPPIV, that was not observed before treatment, as illustrated for BsepR1128C (Fig. 2B). 4-PB Decreases Clinical and Biological Parame- ters of Cholestasis. In all 4 patients, serum BAC and pruritus decreased and serum liver function tests, when altered, treatment with 4-PB had begun. Detailed results are provided in Table 1. In patients 1 and 4, pruritus and serum BAC increased and serum liver tests deteriorated during three episodes of noncompliance and an improvement was observed when therapy was restarted. In both patients, the bad taste of the drug and, especially, the important number of pills to be taken (up to 40 pills a day for a 20-mg daily dose) were reported as the main reason for non- compliance. However, in both cases, patients went back on therapy by themselves because they experi- enced improvement of their medical condition when taking the drug. After celebrating his 18th birthday, patient 3 pre- sented acute alcoholic hepatitis, thereby worsening his liver failure. Subsequently, 4-PB therapy was inter- rupted after 3 months and an LT was performed. Cur- rently, after a follow-up with 4-PB therapy of 53, 51, and 29 months in patients 1, 2, and 4, respectively, the improvement of their medical conditions remains stable. Alpha-fetoprotein remains normal in all patients. No severe side effects were observed.

4-PB Partially Corrects BSEP Canalicular Expres- sion and Improves Histological Injuries. After 3 months of therapy with 4-PB, a liver biopsy was per- formed on patient 1. Histological analysis showed a trend toward a decrease of area of ﬁbrosis, as compared with the liver biopsy performed before treatment with 4-PB (Fig. 3A), in addition to a decrease of cholestasis and giant cell transformation (data not shown). In this patient, partial retargeting of BSEP with therapy was previously shown.15 Analysis of a liver biopsy performed in patient 2 after 30 months of therapy with 4-PB showed a normal BSEP canalicular immunostaining, as well as the absence of canalicular cholestasis and giant cell transformation (Fig. 3B). Minimal lobular ﬁbrosis was observed (Fig. 3B). Because no liver biopsy was performed before 4-PB was started, it is not possible to know whether or not 4-PB therapy modiﬁed liver path- ological ﬁndings observed in patient 2. Patient 4 under- went the ﬁrst before 4-PB was started and the second after 10 months of follow-up, 1 month after 4-PB was restarted (Table 1). Histological analysis revealed a positive canalicular BSEP immuno- staining that was not detected before 4-PB treatment (Fig. 3C) and a decrease of cholestasis and giant cell transformation (data not shown).

4-PB is a clinically approved chaperone that has been shown to be safe when used in patients with urea cycle defects.10 Clinical trials performed in homozy- gous patients with mistargeted CFTRDF508 showed that 4-PB was well tolerated and slightly improved nasal epithelial chloride transport.21 The ability of 4-PB to retarget some missense Bsep (including BsepG982R and BsepT1210P) has mutants been previously reported in a nonhepatocellular line.5,6 Here, we showed that 4-PB increased canalicular expression of BsepG982R, BsepR1128C, and BsepT1210P in a hepatocellular polarized line. Our data also shed light upon the action of UDCA, a widely used “anti- cholestatic” drug.22 Indeed, UDCA was also able to increase canalicular expression of these Bsep mutants, suggesting that UDCA can act as a chemical chaper- one, as previously reported in a mice model of diabe- tes.23 This action of UDCA might explain the trend for a greater efﬁciency of UDCA in PFIC2 patients harboring at least one missense mutation.2 A signiﬁ- effect of UDCA and 4-PB was cant observed in vitro for BsepR1128C and BsepT1210P and, to a lesser extent, for BsepG982R. Further studies might help to assess whether UDCA and 4-PB increased Bsep missense mutant canalicular expression through different mechanisms.24,25 The normal canalicular expression of BsepA257V suggests that this mutation might be pathogenic by altering the function of BSEP. Furthermore, the mother of patient 2, who harbors a heterozygous status for A257V BSEP mutant, experi- enced intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy.26 We did not perform functional analysis of the BA transport ability of these missense mutants. We speculated that G982R, R1128C, and T1210P BSEP mutants retained a residual function and that retargeting with 4-PB would increase biliary BA secretion. In vitro studies suggested that some missense Bsep mutants (including BsepG982R and BsepT1210P) might be functional and that treatment with 4-PB could increase BA transport function.3,7,16 The function increase of transport BsepT1210P mutant observed after 4-PB correlated with an increase of the protein expression level of these mutants.16 Further in vitro studies would be needed to study the effect of 4-PB and UDCA on the transport function of Bsep missense mutants.

Based on these in vitro data, patients were treated with recommended oral doses of 4-PB. The 4 patients were taking UDCA as a ﬁrst-line therapy, which was maintained without a change in dosage. During 4-PB therapy, we observed a decrease of cholestasis in all patients, as assessed by reduction of pruritus and serum BACs, as well as an improvement of serum liver tests. The improvement of pathological injuries (such as cholestasis and giant cell transformation) further suggests the ability of 4-PB to decrease hepatocellular damage in these PFIC2 patients. the effects of 4-PB, especially on itching, were clearly cor- related to compliance. During episodes of noncompli- ance, we observed a deterioration of clinical and biological conditions that was reversed when treatment was taken again correctly (Table 1). Reduction of itch- ing did not closely correlate with serum BAC in patient 1. In the patient reported on by Naomi et al., despite improvement of itching with 4-PB, neither BA levels decreased in serum.16 nor autotaxin (ATX) Recently, 4-PB therapy was reported to decrease itch- ing in 3 patients with PFIC1. In these patients, BSEP protein-level expression increased with 4-PB, but serum levels of BA and of ATX were not altered.27 The mechanisms underlying the improvement of itch- ing observed with 4-PB in PFIC1 and in PFIC2 patients remain to be identiﬁed. In line with previous reports, which mainly concern patients with urea cycle disorders, 4-PB treatment was well tolerated. No severe side effects were observed within our experience of more than 10 patient-years with 4-PB.10,15,16 BSEP immunostaining performed in patients 2 and 4 during therapy with 4-PB showed a canalicular expression of BSEP that was not detected In patient 2, we in patient 4. before treatment

assumed that the effect of 4-PB relied on a retargeting effect on BSEPG982R. However, as previously reported for BSEPWT,27,28 we cannot exclude an effect of 4-PB on BSEPA257V that was correctly addressed to the can- alicular membrane in Can 10 cells before any treat- ment. These results are in line with our preliminary report regarding patient 1 and further suggest that 4-PB is able to retarget some missense BSEP mutants at the canalicular membrane.15 Biliary BAC measured in 2 patients indicated that, with 4-PB therapy, biliary BA secretion increased; this is most likely owing to the ability of retargeted mutants to transport BAs into bile. However, because bile of patient 2 has not been analyzed before therapy, we cannot assess the contribu- tion of 4-PB in the nearly normal biliary BA secretion we observed in this patient. Taken together, these results the improvement of cholestasis observed in the 4 patients most likely relied on the ability of 4-PB to retarget to the canalicular membrane missense BSEP mutants retained within the hepato- function of BA cytes transport.

Our results show that a novel therapy with a chaper- one drug may be efﬁcient and safe in the long term and may represent an alternative to—or delay—LT in selected PFIC2 patients. These data constitute proof of concept a mutation-speciﬁc pharmacotherapy aimed at partially increasing canalicular expression of a mistargeted missense BSEP mutant can be successfully offered to patients after validation in a cellular model. In a personalized medicine perspective, 4-PB should be further evaluated in selected patients with PFIC2 and benign recurrent intrahepatic cholestasis type 2 (BRIC2, a mild phenotype of ABCB11 biallelic mutations).1- 3,5,8,9,14,16,18 As suggested by in vitro studies, 4-PB might also be a useful drug in management of patients with other liver diseases, hepatocellular in origin, owing to missense mutations resulting in mistrafﬁcking of a mutant protein, such as PFIC1, PFIC3, and Wilson’s disease.12-14,20 The search for other chaperone drugs that might be efﬁcient alone or in association with 4- PB, such as UDCA, also deserves consideration.14,18 thank Dr. Olivier Bernard and Dr. Dalila Habes (CHU Bic^etre, France), Dr. Agathe Jobert (H^opital de Saint Nazaire, France), and Dr. S(cid:2)ebastien Fournier-Favre (CHU Montpellier, France) for referral and/or care of patients 1, 2, and 3, thank Dr. Bruno Stieger respectively.
